description:
## Theory
As seen in the RML tutorial, including properties in the RDF from JSONs may become tricky when the JSONs are not plain or flat. In the mapping the values of the JSON are referenced by means of [JSON Path expressions](https://jsonpath.com/). 
For the sample JSON to access the value of ***key1*** in RML the mapping should specify **"k1"**, instead to access ***nested*** the mapping should specify **"key2.nested"**. 
```json
{
	"key1" : 33,
	"key2" : {
		"nested" : 44
	}
}
```
## Hands-on
### Task
Complete the mapping below for generating triplets containing the names and the surfaces as shown in the expected results section.
### JSON file content
```json
[
  {
	"name": "Oneonta",
	"features": {
		"surface": {
			"value": 90.16,
			"units": "Km2"
		},
		"population": {
			"amount": "1,812",
			"date": 2018
		}
	},
	"location": {
		"latitude": "44.9625428",
		"longitude": "-74.4168577"
	}
  },
  {
	"name": "Iowa",
	"features": {
		"surface": {
			"value": 167.2,
			"units": "Km2"
		},
		"population": {
			"amount": "133,611",
			"date": 2020
		}
	},
	"location": {
		"latitude": "29.6862705",
		"longitude": "-82.319746"
	}
  }...
]
```
